{"id": "1522847204761669653", "channel_id": "1522286581111717888", "author_id": "1437487264023318668", "author_name": "vxvendetta97", "content": "Thais also can't target derived cards, but his exalt is still more limiting in most situations, and a bit harder to charge.\nMaybe they could change how Crescendo and his soulforge works. In place of 3 aliemus when you play a Crescendo card, and up to 5 activation per turn with insights. They could charge 5 aliemus and lower the cap to 3, so you can get the full 15 aliemus with only 3 uses of insight.", "timestamp": "2026-07-04T06:11:06.748000+00:00", "type": 19, "thread_id": "1522286581111717888", "mentions": ["233217233583734785"], "reply_to": "1522724483419607041"}
{"id": "1522851704595546232", "channel_id": "1522286581111717888", "author_id": "233217233583734785", "author_name": "lavache.", "content": "<:Brown_think:1459080117308620996> I feel that the real problem with his exalt limitation which cannot target the same card twice is that it has diminishing returns in most decks -- often there are a couple of high priority cards for double cast, beyond which it becomes, sure nice to have a cheap double cast but it doesn't do much... so if they must keep this restriction, perhaps having an incentive to spread out his crescendos, say, linking them so that if any crescendo is played, the rest in hand are auto cast for free (like a symphony?)...", "timestamp": "2026-07-04T06:28:59.592000+00:00", "thread_id": "1522286581111717888"}
